Inclusion and exclusion criteria for thrombolysis:

mnemonic for exclusion criteria:

  • History, Head CT, Haematology and Clinical.

No the footnote about potentially disabling defects!


  • The disease process results in crypt hyperplasia and villous atrophy.

Symptoms

Most commonly asymptomatic; but patients will show signs of malabsorption.
Many and will be diagnosed upon evaluation for macrocytic anaemia. (due to malabsorption).
Mouth ulcers, angular stomatits.

If symptomatic, diarrhoea, steatorrhoea, abdominal pain and weight loss in severe disease.
Can present at any age.
Female predominance. Peak is at 40-50 years.

Complications

Osteoporosis
parasaesthesia, ataxia, polyneuropathy.
Associated with autoimmune diseases: IBD, primary biliary cholangitis, chonic liver disease, ILD, epilepsy.

Diagnosis:

gold standard: small bowel biopsy.
Serology is very useful : endomysial and tissue transglutaminase antibodies.

Pulmonary eosinophilia (PE)

Pulmonary eosinophilia (PE) is defined as the infiltration of eosinophils into the lung tissue; Source

PE can be divided into primary and secondary based on causes:

Primary PE Secondary PE
Acute eosinophilic pneumonia [[General Medicine 1#Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis]]
Chronic eosinophilic pneumonia Parasites
EGPA Medications
Hypereosinophilic syndrome (HES) Radiation effects
Malignancies

[!INFO] Commonest cause of pulmonary eosinophilia is parasitic infestation.
Drugs causing PE

  • NSAIDS, aspirin
  • ACE inhibitors
  • TMP-SMX
  • others

Loffler syndrome / Loeffler syndrome

#2021SBR-NOV Q13

Also called simple pulmonary eosinophilia Source

  • Acute (<2 weeks), mild ilness(just fever and cough)
  • with transient pulmonary radiographic opacities and
  • peripheral blood eosinophilia associated with
  • allergic reaction to intestinal parasites, commonly described with Ascariasis and Strongyloidiasis.

Resolves spotaneously!

If the course is more prolonged, the disease is called prolonged pulmonary eosinophilia.

Tropical pulmonary eosinophilia (Weingarten syndrome)

[!INFO] The essentials:

  • Tropical pulmonary eosinophilia (TPE) is a hyperresponsive pulmonary syndrome in response to trapped microfilariae within the lung tissue
  • characterized by nocturnal cough, dyspnea, and wheezing.
  • Occurs particularly in young adult males, with a male to female ratio of 4:1 Source
  • Diagnosis:
    • Travel history to a lymphatic filariasis endemic region,
    • peripheral eosinophilia >3,000/mm3, and
    • elevated serum IgE and antifilarial antibodies level is crucial for diagnosis.
    • Extrapulmonary features are present but not very common: #hepatosplenomegaly #lymphadenopathy
  • Treatment with diethylcarbamazine has an excellent response but untreated, it can case pulmonary fibrosis.
  • Source

Hypereosinophilic syndrome

Hypoglycaemic symptoms

Neurogenic (autonomic) symptoms: tremmor, tachycardia, sweating, anxiety, hunger,
Neuroglycopaenic symptoms: weakness, tiredness, dizziness, poor concentration, inapporriate (even drunken like) behaviour, coma and eath.

Rarely, focal features can occur.

focal neurological signs, such as hemiparesis, aphasia, and blindness

[!TIP] PBC - the C can stand for Cirrhocis or Cholangitis.
But Fatigue is a prominent presenting symptom. Icterus and pruritus are late signs.

  • Presentation: Asymptomatic with #hepatomegaly and raised ALP. (raised ALP is often the only abnormal investigation)

#2021SBR-NOV Q16

Epidemiology

3:1 Female predominance between 30 to 50 years.

Pathogenesis

Chronic endothelial damage with IL-2 producing cells migrating into the tissues because of increased expression of adhesion molecules.
This sets up chronic inflammation leading to a production of a soup of cytokines -> fibroblast activation.

  1. Vascular - majority have Raynaud's phenomemon <- Seen in almost all, can even precede other symptoms.
  2. Fibrogenic - skin changes

Presentation

Mainly 2 types:
ANA is positive in 90% of both types.
RF is positive in 30%.

Limited cutaneous scleroderma 70%

ACA (anticentromere antibodies) present in most.

  • Skin
    • Skin involvement limited to hands, face, feet and forearms.
    • Beak like nose and micostomia
    • Painful digital ulcers.
    • telangiectasiaa nd dilated nail fold capillary loops.
    • Digital ischemia
  • Systemic features:
    • GI tract inolvement is common
    • Pulmonary hypertension

Diffuse cutaneous scleroderma 30%

Antitopoisomerase and anti-RNA polymerase.

Stars with swelling and sclerosis of fingers rapidly followed by more extensive skin thickening which can involve most of the body.

Early involvement of other organs:

  • GI -
    • oesophageal
    • Anal incontinence
    • Dilation of bowel with atony
  • Renal

Nearly universal. Thickening of skin of fingers, hands and face are earliest manifestations.
Digital vasculopathy - Raynaud's phenomenon - is very common. Severity of episodes increases over time.
Eventually, ischemic pain -> ulcers -> necrosis
Severe raynauds can be treated with anti vasospasmic agents : CCB, ACEi.

Joint pain, stiffness and contractures of small and large joints, tendinits, tendon friction rubs.
commonest site of GI involvement: oesophagus* -> symptoms are reduced with PPIs.

[!INFO] Pulmonary involvement accounts for 50% of deaths in these patients.

Bosentan, warfarin !? Source-Warfarin can be used in PAH , oxygen, heart lung or lung transplant.
Pulmonary fibrosis is treated with immunosuupression - clyclophosphamide / azathioprine.

anticoagulation may be associated with improved survival in idiopathic PAH but may be associated with reduced survival in systemic sclerosis-associated PAH. [Source](anticoagulation may be associated with improved survival in idiopathic PAH but may be associated with reduced survival in systemic sclerosis-associated PAH)

  • Used to be the most common cause of death in these patients.

ACEi is the drug of choice for managing hypertension.
Scleroderma is treated with organ-based symptomatic therapy. There is no cure.
However, patients with diffuse skin involvement and/or severe inflammatory organ involvement are usually treated with systemic immunosuppressive therapy.
